## Volga

The [Volga](/Volga) is not merely a river; it is an artery, a historical narrative etched into the very soul of [Eastern Europe](/Eastern_Europe). To speak of it is to speak of empires, of migrations, of the relentless march of time itself. It is the longest river in [Europe](/Europe), a serpentine titan that carves its path through the vast expanse of [Russia](/Russia) before finally surrendering its waters to the [Caspian Sea](/Caspian_Sea). Its significance transcends geographical boundaries, weaving itself into the tapestry of [culture](/culture), [economy](/economy), and [geopolitics](/geopolitics) for centuries.

### Course

The [Volga](/Volga) embarks on its grand journey from the [Valdai Hills](/Valdai_Hills), a relatively modest elevation in northwestern [Russia](/Russia), not far from the [cities](/cities) of [Tver](/Tver) and [Moscow](/Moscow). From these humble beginnings, it gains momentum, fed by countless tributaries that swell its volume as it meanders southeastward across the expansive [East European Plain](/East_European_Plain). Its course is not a straight line, but a series of deliberate curves and meanders, a testament to the geological forces that have shaped the land over millennia.

Early in its trajectory, the [Volga](/Volga) is augmented by the waters of the [Selizharovka River](/Selizharovka_River), marking the true commencement of its navigable length. It then flows through a series of significant [reservoirs](/reservoirs), artificial lakes created by [dams](/dams) that have profoundly altered its natural flow and ecological balance. These include the [Ivankovo Reservoir](/Ivankovo_Reservoir), often referred to as the [Moscow Sea](/Moscow_Sea) due to its proximity to the capital, followed by the [Uglich Reservoir](/Uglich_Reservoir), the [Rybinsk Reservoir](/Rybinsk_Reservoir) – one of the largest artificial lakes in the world – the [Gorky Reservoir](/Gorky_Reservoir), the [Cheboksary Reservoir](/Cheboksary_Reservoir), and finally the [Kuybyshev Reservoir](/Kuybyshev_Reservoir), also known as the [Samara Sea](/Samara_Sea), which is the largest reservoir by surface area globally. These man-made lakes, while facilitating [hydroelectric power](/hydroelectric_power) generation and [navigation](/navigation), have also led to the inundation of vast [territories](/territories), displacing [communities](/communities) and altering [ecosystems](/ecosystems).

The river's path takes it past numerous [cities](/cities), each bearing witness to its historical and economic importance. Among these are [Yaroslavl](/Yaroslavl), a [UNESCO World Heritage Site](/UNESCO_World_Heritage_Site) steeped in [history](/history); [Nizhny Novgorod](/Nizhny_Novgorod), a major [industrial](/industrial) and [cultural](/cultural) hub; [Kazan](/Kazan), the vibrant capital of [Tatarstan](/Tatarstan); [Ulyanovsk](/Ulyanovsk), the birthplace of [Vladimir Lenin](/Vladimir_Lenin); [Samara](/Samara), another significant [industrial](/industrial) center; and [Saratov](/Saratov), a [port city](/port_city) with a rich [past](/past).

As the [Volga](/Volga) approaches its terminus, it undergoes a dramatic transformation, branching out into an extensive delta. This vast network of channels, islands, and wetlands is a testament to the river's immense volume and its final act of dispersal into the saline embrace of the [Caspian Sea](/Caspian_Sea). The [Volga Delta](/Volga_Delta) is a [biodiversity hotspot](/biodiversity_hotspot), supporting a unique array of flora and fauna adapted to its [brackish](/brackish) waters.

